docs.abstract: For decades, films about transgender people tended to be sensationalistic. A newer crop is more celebratory — and opening doors for its young subjects.
docs.snippet: For decades, films about transgender people tended to be sensationalistic. A newer crop is more celebratory — and opening doors for its young subjects.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the first part of the documentary series “Always Jane,” Jane Noury, a high school student in suburban New Jersey, hangs out with friends, contemplates college — maybe the School of Visual Arts? — and works at the local Panera. She dreams of being a director. Near the end of Part 1, Jane also learns that she will have to miss commencement; it falls on the same day as her gender confirmation surgery.

headline.main: ‘Always Jane’ Is Part of a New Generation of Trans Documentaries

docs.abstract: Jeff Bezos, the billionaire founder of Amazon who recently flew to space, promised to invest $2 billion toward restoring natural habitats and transforming food systems. He also said Amazon aims to power its operations with renewable energies by 2025.
